            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Meera Sharma\u2019s story is one of quiet resilience, forged in the striving immigrant landscape of the East Bay. The only daughter of parents who ran a small grocery store in Union City, she was raised on the scent of cardamom and the constant hum of the cash register. Her parents instilled in her a formidable work ethic and the expectation that she would achieve a stability they never had. She enrolled at San Jose State, pursuing a degree in Business Administration, determined to make them proud.\n\nHer trajectory was abruptly altered during her sophomore year when her father suffered a major heart attack. The family\u2019s modest savings were decimated by medical bills, and Meera made the difficult decision to leave college. She took an entry-level administrative job at a mortgage brokerage in Fremont to help support her family. It was meant to be temporary, but she discovered an unexpected aptitude for the intricate dance of finance. She was sharp, meticulous, and possessed a calm empathy that reassured anxious homebuyers.\n\nShe devoured every piece of knowledge, earning her loan officer license and steadily climbing the ranks through sheer grit and performance. Her career became her education. After nearly a decade of supporting her parents and securing their retirement, Meera finally made a move for herself. She chose San Francisco, a city that felt like a reward for her years of sacrifice.\n\nNow, at 38, she lives in a tastefully decorated one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley. Her days are structured and demanding. She takes the 21-Hayes Muni bus to her Financial District office, spending her commute listening to podcasts on economics or losing herself in a novel. As a Senior Loan Officer, she is a respected and trusted figure, known for her ability to untangle the most complex financial situations.\n\nHer evenings are her own. She might join friends for dinner in her neighborhood, attend a yoga class, or simply enjoy the view from her window. While she is successful and content, Meera dreams of experiences beyond balance sheets. She hopes to one day travel extensively, particularly through the villages of Rajasthan where her grandparents were from. And, for herself, she quietly considers finishing her degree online\u2014not for her career, but for the sense of completion that the young woman she once was deserved."
